President Muhammadu Buhari has noted the poor welfare and working conditions of the nation’s judiciary, assuring the situation would be given serious attention. Buhari gave the assurance when he received the chairman and representatives of the Body of Benchers at the Presidential Villa, also cautioned the judiciary to consider the state of the economy from the resources to attend to their needs would come from. According to a statement by his Senior Special Assistant on Media and Publicity, Mallam Garba Shehu, the President described the state of the economy as “currently battling insecurity, corruption and economic challenges,” aggravated by the COVID-19 and the war in Ukraine. He said a democratic government like the one he leads “standing on a tripod comprising the Executive, Legislature and Judiciary, cannot stand where one of its three pillars, the Judiciary is not properly nurtured, maintained and sustained to deliver on its very pivotal constitutional duties.”   CSO makes case for seniority in picking new Accountant…     We’re not aware of such plans, says Education Ministry’s…     Four injured as NURTW, NDLEA operatives clash in Osogbo park   He promised to act quickly on the report of the committee he set up on his own back in 2018 to review the welfare and working conditions of the judiciary. “Let me assure you that the issues would be given due and urgent attention within the resources available to government.” The President congratulated the Body of Benchers on the successful completion of the “Benchers’ complex at Jabi,” a building described as impressive that would house the body and provide conference facilities and accepted their invitation to personally commission the structure. Chairman of the Body of Benchers, Wole Olanipekun, Senior Advocate of Nigeria, described the condition under which judges, especially the Justices of the Supreme Court work as pathetic, appalling and below the minimum standards that are required.